Finally, simulated samples and real cases are analyzed to test the practicality of the N-CQD-based fluorescence detection methods. The simulated samples are prepared by adding different PA concentrations(0.01, 0.03, 0.05, 0.07, and 0.09 mg/g) to washed sand samples (Table 1
                        ). The N-CQDs can accurately detect the PA content in simulated samples, presenting a low CV value and a good recovery rate (90.0 % ∼ 103.0 %). The real explosion case is the analysis of site explosion residual dust, first using the national standard method (standard name: GB/T 5750.8–2006) to determine the PA content in the explosion dust quantitatively (0.076 ± 0.003 mg/g), then employing N-CQDs to determine the PA concentration in the explosion dust. Table 2
                         suggests that the results of the two quantitative methods are consistent, and the actual sample complexity does not affect the PA detection by N-CQDs, validating its strong detection ability in practical applications.
